===Etymology===
The place is first mentioned by this name in the late 12th century (as {{bor|de|gml|Berlyn}}).

The origin is {{unk|de|nocap=1}}. {{der|de|sla|-}} by the suffix {{m|sla-pro|*-inъ}}.

According to (incorrect) [[folk etymology]], the name is derived from the {{m|de|Bär||bear}} that is the symbol of the city.

In a popular etymology of Germanists, it is derived from a {{der|de|pox|-}} stem {{m|pox||*berl-}} ~ {{m|pox||*birl-|t=swamp}}, for which lexical item there is no evidence in Polabian nor in any Slavic language. Closest to that would be an unknown simple of {{m|sla-pro|*bьrlogъ|t=cave}}.

Attested vocabulary is {{cog|pox|poro|t=swamp, bog}}. {{m|sla-pro|*bělь}} also meant a “swampy meadow” or “white field”, which fits the location at the {{w|Margraviate of Brandenburg|''märkische Streusandbüchse''}}, the “Margraviate pounce box” notorious for its sandy soil, and is also the noun behind {{w|lang=de|Belitz|''Belitz''}}.

